<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p>Everything you need to know about TikTok brand deal pricing</p>
<h3>How much should I charge for a TikTok brand deal?</h3>
<p>It depends on your follower count and engagement rate. Creators with 10K-50K followers typically charge £395-£1,970 per post, 50K-100K followers charge £1,970-£3,940, and 100K-500K followers charge £3,940-£11,810. High engagement (8%+) can add a 50-100% premium on top of these base rates.</p>
<h3>What factors affect brand deal pricing?</h3>
<p>The main factors are follower count, engagement rate, content niche, deliverable type, usage rights, exclusivity, and timing. Q4 holiday season (October to December) typically pays 20-30% more due to higher brand budgets. Finance and technology niches command 2-3x higher rates than entertainment or gaming.</p>
<h3>What is a good engagement rate for brand deals?</h3>
<p>5%+ is considered strong for brand deal negotiations. 8%+ is excellent and can command 1.5-2x higher rates than average. Below 3% may reduce your rate below average, as brands increasingly prioritize engagement over raw follower count when evaluating creators.</p>
<h3>Should I charge more for usage rights?</h3>
<p>Yes, absolutely. Organic reposts add 25-50% to your base rate, paid ad rights add 50-100%, whitelisting adds 50-100%, and exclusivity adds 25-50%. Always ask about intended usage before quoting a price, as usage rights can significantly increase the total value of a deal.</p>
<h3>How do I negotiate brand deal rates?</h3>
<p>Start 20-30% above your target rate to leave room for negotiation. Lead with your engagement rate rather than follower count, as brands value engaged audiences more. Ask about usage rights before giving a price. Have a professional media kit ready with your analytics, past collaborations, and audience demographics.</p>
<h3>What niches command the highest brand deal rates?</h3>
<p>Finance and investing command the highest rates at 2-3x the average, followed by technology at 1.5-2.5x, health and wellness at 1.5-2x, and business at 1.5-2x. Beauty and fashion sit at the 1x average baseline. Entertainment and gaming typically pay below average at 0.5-1x.</p>
<h3>Do brand deals pay more than Creator Fund?</h3>
<p>Yes, significantly more. A creator with 50K followers might earn £8-£16 per month from Creator Fund but £1,970-£3,940 per brand deal post. Brand deals are typically the largest income stream for most creators, accounting for 50-70% of total earnings.</p>
<h3>How many brand deals should I do per month?</h3>
<p>2-4 deals per month is sustainable for most mid-tier creators. Too many sponsored posts can hurt your engagement rate and audience trust. A good rule of thumb is keeping sponsored content to no more than 20-30% of your total posts to maintain authenticity.</p>
